###Strategy

The ratio between the area of a sector and the area of the whole circle is proportional to the ratio between the sector's central angle (let's call it $\theta$) and the central angle of the whole circle (which is always $360\degree$).

$\begin{array}{rcl}
&\text{sector}
\\
\begin{array}{c}\text{central angle}\\ \text{measure} \\ \text{(in degrees)}\end{array}
&\overbrace{\underbrace{\!\!\!\!\!\left\{ 
\dfrac{ \purpleD{\text{Angle}_{\text{sector}}}}{360}=\dfrac{\goldE{\text{Area}_{\text{sector}}}}{\blueE{\text{Area}_{\text{circle}}}}
\right\}\!\!\!\!\!}}
&{\text{area}}
\\
&\text{whole circle}
\end{array}$

We are given that $\maroonD{\text{radius}=12\,\text{cm}}$ and $\purpleD{\text{Angle}_{\text{sector}}=175\degree}$. Let's use the radius to find the area of the circle, then plug that in the equation and solve for the area of the sector.

